In Title 274 of this book, controversies of this kind are treated; and the rule given is this, that if the ships and the lading both belong to the enemy, the matter is plain, and they become the property of the captorS. If the ship belong to a neutral, the goods to an enemy, the belligerent may compel the ship to go into a port of his own, paying the navigators for the freight. If, on the other hand, it is an enemy's ship, with the goods of a neutral, the ship is to be ransomed, and if the navigators refuse this, they may be taken into a port of the captors, and the captor must be paid for the use of the ship.

In the year 1438, when the Hollanders were at war with Lubeck and other cities on the Baltic and the Elbe, they decided in full Senate, that goods of neutrals found in the enemy's ships were not good prize, and that law was afterwards main- tained. So also in 1597, the king of Denmarkjndged‚ when he sent an embassy to the Hollanders, and their allies, asserting for his subjects the right of carrying goods into Spain, with which the Hollanders were then in fierce war.
